:::summary
Michelangelo di Lodovico Buonarroti Simoni (1475–1564) was the supreme genius of the Italian Renaissance — sculptor, painter, architect, and poet — whose works *David*, the *Pietà*, and the Sistine Chapel ceiling stand among the greatest achievements in the history of human art. Driven by an almost superhuman creative energy and a profound Christian faith, Michelangelo explored the beauty of the human body as a vehicle for expressing the divine, and no artist before or since has so powerfully united physical grandeur with spiritual intensity. He lived to 88 in an age when few survived past 40, and nearly every work of his career is a masterpiece.
:::

